<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Uttarakhand</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Land of Gods</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Uttarakhand, the "Land of Gods," is a northern state renowned for its sacred temples, majestic Himalayan mountains and spiritual significance. Nestled in the foothills of the Himalayas, Uttarakhand captivates with snow-capped peaks, pristine rivers, lush forests and serene hill stations. Known as the "Pilgrimage Capital of India," Uttarakhand is home to numerous Hindu sacred sites and ancient temples. From the holy confluence of rivers at Haridwar to the spiritual heights of Rishikesh, from the adventure paradise of Auli to the serene lakes of Nainital, Uttarakhand offers diverse experiences. The state's rich cultural heritage, traditional handicrafts, vibrant festivals and authentic cuisine showcase the Himalayan way of life. Uttarakhand's commitment to preserving its natural beauty while promoting sustainable tourism creates a unique destination where spirituality meets adventure.</p>
</section>

<section id="weather" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lWeather">Climate &amp; Best Time</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="weatherTitle">When to Visit <em>Uttarakhand</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="weatherNote" style="margin-bottom:0">Uttarakhand experiences monsoon (June-September), pleasant autumn (October-November), cold winter (December-February) and mild spring (March-May). March to May and September to November offer ideal weather with clear skies, comfortable temperatures and excellent visibility for trekking and sightseeing.</p>
  <div class="wgrid" id="wGrid"></div>
</section>

